Linux Driver for Cisco Systems Inc. VIC Ethernet NIC
====================================================

Known Issues
============

Multiple Interfaces on Same Ethernet Broadcast Network
------------------------------------------------------
Due to the default ARP behavior on Linux, it is not possible to have
one system on two IP networks in the same Ethernet broadcast domain
(non-partitioned switch) behave as expected.  All Ethernet interfaces
will respond to IP traffic for any IP address assigned to the system.
This results in unbalanced receive traffic.

If you have multiple interfaces in a server, turn on ARP
filtering by entering:

    net.ipv4.conf.all.arp_filter = 1

to the file /etc/sysctl.conf and restart the system.


__tmpXXX Interface Names
------------------------
Redhat distributions include a udev helper to rename network devices
based on information found in /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-eth
configuration files.  A device can be renamed if there is a ifcfg-eth
file with a HWADDR field that matches the device's MAC address.  If a
device already exists with the target name, the existing device
is renamed __tmpXXX, where XXX is a random number.  It is assumed that
the renamed __tmpXXX device would also have a matching ifcfg-eth file
and would therefore be renamed again to match the DEVICE name in
ifcfg-eth.  Any leftover __tmpXXX devices is an indication that there
is a problem with the ifcfg-eth files and is fixed by assigning each
device with an ifcfg-eth file with the correct MAC address in the 
HWADDR field.


Configured Interfaces Don't Come Up
-----------------------------------
On Redhat distributions, changing the device names in the ifcfg-eth 
files may result in a mismatch between the kernel assigned interface 
names and the ones in the ifcfg-eth files and unexpected things may 
happen. One such known issue is that some of the interfaces fail to 
come up on loading the driver.


Setting Interrupt Coalesce Timer for Interfaces
-----------------------------------------------
For those interfaces running in MSI/Legacy interrupt mode, the interrupt
vector for the transmit and receive queues is the same. Hence there is a
restriction on the way we set the interrupt coalesce timer values for such
interfaces. Both tx-usecs and rx-usecs have to set with the same value.

$ethtool -C ethx tx-usecs=y rx-usecs=y

There is no such restriction for the interfaces in MSI-X mode

$ethtool -C ethx tx-usecs=y rx-usecs=z


Iperf multicast UDP test dropped packets
----------------------------------------
Under UDP stress test, The Linux system may drop UDP packets due to not 
enough socket receive buffers. These drops show up under receive errors 
in 'netstat -su' output. 

You can increase the Linux kernel's default socket buffer sizes for UDP by 
increasing the values in /proc/sys/net/core/rmem_default and rmem_max.
For the new values to persist across reboots you will have to add it to 
/etc/sysctl.conf

IP_ADD_MEMBERSHIP failures
--------------------------
On a Linux host, the max no. of multicast groups that the host interfaces
can subscribe to is defined in /proc/sys/net/ipv4/igmp_max_memberships,
with a default value of 20. Exceeding this limit can cause any service that
does multicast registrations on host interfaces run into IP_ADD_MEMBERSHIP
failures.

One such example is the avahi-daemon service on Linux distributions. On enic 
driver load, avahi-daemon registers the IPv4 mNDS multicast group on every 
interface. When there are large no. of interfaces, there is a possibility of
exceeding the igmp_max_memberships limit. In such a case, avahi-daemon fails 
to join mDNS multicast groups on one or more interfaces. The following error 
messages appear in /var/log/messages.

avahi-daemon: Joining mDNS multicast group on interface ethX.IPv4 with address Y
avahi-daemon: IP_ADD_MEMBERSHIP failed: No buffer space available

The solution is to increase the limit in /proc/sys/net/ipv4/igmp_max_memberships

For immediate effect:
	#echo xxx > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/igmp_max_memberships
or
For persistence across reboots: 
	Add to /etc/sysctl.conf and reboot host
